Model.P:
Automotive Suspension
This example shows how to model a simplified half-car model that includes an independent front and rear vertical suspension. The model also includes body pitch and bounce degrees of freedom. The example provides a description of the model to show how simulation can be used for investigating ride characteristics. In conjunction with a powertrain simulation, the model could investigate longitudinal shuffle resulting from changes in throttle setting.

Object.P: Half-Car Suspension The spring and damping rates for an individual wheel are entered below. Their combined effect as applied to two wheels at the specified distance from the center of mass is computed. The distance should be specified as positive if the subsystem is oriented such that increasing z corresponds to increasing theta, negative otherwise.
See "Using Simulink and Stateflow in Automotive Applications" for a mathematical derivation of the subsystem operation. Contact your MathWorks distributor to obtain a copy.
